AB  - This article presents the development of a Digital Twin (DT)-based tool for optimizing scheduling in solid bulk export port terminals. The approach integrates agent-based simulation with the Ant Colony System (ACS) metaheuristic to efficiently plan railway unloading, stockyard storage, and maritime shipping. The model interacts with operational data, anticipating issues and aiding decision-making. Validation was performed using real data from a port terminal in Brazil, yielding compatible results and reducing port stay duration. Tests were based on a Baseline Scenario, aligned with a mineral export terminal, for ACS parameter calibration, along with three additional scenarios: direct shipment, preventive maintenance, and a simultaneous route from stockyard to ships. This study highlights DT's potential to modernize port operations, offering practical support in large-scale logistics environments.
ER  - 

